00:01:05.840 --> 00:01:08.320
But let me now introduce
you to Chris Impey.

00:01:08.320 --> 00:01:11.370
Chris is a University
Distinguished professor

00:01:11.370 --> 00:01:14.350
whose research interests
are observational cosmology,

00:01:14.350 --> 00:01:17.280
gravitational lensing, and
the evolution of structure

00:01:17.280 --> 00:01:18.540
of galaxies.

00:01:18.540 --> 00:01:23.320
He has 160 refereed publications
and 60 conference proceedings,

00:01:23.320 --> 00:01:25.380
and his work has been
supported by $20 million

00:01:25.380 --> 00:01:27.940
in grants from NASA and NSF.

00:01:27.940 --> 00:01:30.020
He has won 11 teaching
awards, and he

00:01:30.020 --> 00:01:31.770
has been heavily
involved in curriculum

00:01:31.770 --> 00:01:34.530
and instructional
technology development.

00:01:34.530 --> 00:01:38.260
Chris is past President of the
American Astronomical Society.

00:01:38.260 --> 00:01:40.560
He has also been a
National Science Foundation

00:01:40.560 --> 00:01:44.600
distinguished teaching scholar,
a Phi Beta Kappa visiting

00:01:44.600 --> 00:01:48.370
scholar, and the Carnegie
counsel on teachings Arizona

00:01:48.370 --> 00:01:49.770
professor of the year.

00:01:49.770 --> 00:01:53.060
He has written over 30
popular articles in cosmology

00:01:53.060 --> 00:01:55.180
and astrobiology,
and co-authored

00:01:55.180 --> 00:01:57.590
two introductory textbooks.

00:01:57.590 --> 00:02:00.410
He is the author of two popular
books, "The Living Cosmos"

00:02:00.410 --> 00:02:03.510
and "How It Ends,"
and in 2009, he

00:02:03.510 --> 00:02:05.770
was elected Fellow of
the American Association

00:02:05.770 --> 00:02:08.039
for the Advancement of Science.

00:02:08.039 --> 00:02:10.820
In addition to all of
this, instead of sleeping,

00:02:10.820 --> 00:02:12.860
Chris regularly
teaches cosmology

00:02:12.860 --> 00:02:16.550
to Buddhist monks at the
monastery in the Himalayas,

00:02:16.550 --> 00:02:18.110
has played pingpong at Mt.

00:02:18.110 --> 00:02:21.030
Everest base camp, and
I have to warn you,

00:02:21.030 --> 00:02:25.900
his Scottish accent emerges
after drinking single scotch.

00:02:25.900 --> 00:02:26.689
Chris.

00:02:26.689 --> 00:02:37.680
[AUDIENCE CHEERING]

00:02:37.680 --> 00:02:38.490
OK.

00:02:38.490 --> 00:02:40.460
I'm really pleased to be here.

00:02:40.460 --> 00:02:42.380
So I want to start with history.

00:02:42.380 --> 00:02:45.780
A guy gave some amazing
and beautiful story

00:02:45.780 --> 00:02:48.700
of the philosophical
and religious traditions

00:02:48.700 --> 00:02:51.167
that underpin our
ideas of the universe.

00:02:51.167 --> 00:02:53.250
I'm going to give a little
more history leading up

00:02:53.250 --> 00:02:54.870
to the idea of the Big Bang.

00:02:54.870 --> 00:02:57.250
And the fundamental
dichotomy in this subject

00:02:57.250 --> 00:03:00.460
is a profound issue that
it's easy to understand.

00:03:00.460 --> 00:03:03.490
It's the distinction between
whether the universe is

00:03:03.490 --> 00:03:05.040
finite or infinite.

00:03:05.040 --> 00:03:08.200
And that's either
in time or space.

00:03:08.200 --> 00:03:09.830
And worrying about
this is essentially

00:03:09.830 --> 00:03:10.910
what cosmologists do.

00:03:10.910 --> 00:03:12.590
Normal people get
up and they worry

00:03:12.590 --> 00:03:15.040
about paying their mortgage,
and paying the college bills,

00:03:15.040 --> 00:03:16.700
cosmologists, people
like me, get up

00:03:16.700 --> 00:03:19.060
in a cold sweat worrying
about whether the universe is

00:03:19.060 --> 00:03:20.520
infinite or not.

00:03:20.520 --> 00:03:23.360
Does the universe go on forever
or does it have a limit?

00:03:23.360 --> 00:03:26.150
These questions have
been asked for centuries.

00:03:26.150 --> 00:03:30.150
Plato's colleague, Archytas,
said, imagine a warrior

00:03:30.150 --> 00:03:32.780
with a spear at the
edge of the universe,

00:03:32.780 --> 00:03:35.210
and he hurls his spear swiftly.

00:03:35.210 --> 00:03:37.110
Do you imagine that
it goes forever?

00:03:37.110 --> 00:03:38.290
And into what?

00:03:38.290 --> 00:03:40.350
Or does it hit something,
or bounce back?

00:03:40.350 --> 00:03:42.482
And in that case,
what's the limit?

00:03:42.482 --> 00:03:44.690
So you can see either way
there's a bit of a problem.

00:03:44.690 --> 00:03:46.570
It's either infinite, and
what's all that about?

00:03:46.570 --> 00:03:48.569
Or there's an end, and
what's the end and what's

00:03:48.569 --> 00:03:49.600
beyond the end?

00:03:49.600 --> 00:03:51.880
And cosmologists wrestle
with the same questions.

00:03:51.880 --> 00:03:55.920
And I'll attempt to
partially answer them today.

00:03:55.920 --> 00:03:58.840
When Copernicus replaced
this, the geocentric model,

00:03:58.840 --> 00:04:03.360
with the heliocentric model,
it was a revolutionary move.

00:04:03.360 --> 00:04:06.150
The word revolution in
our modern sense of it,

00:04:06.150 --> 00:04:08.500
as violent political
and social upheaval,

00:04:08.500 --> 00:04:11.770
refers to Copernicus's
book on the revolutions.

00:04:11.770 --> 00:04:14.660
Because what he did was
not just astronomical,

00:04:14.660 --> 00:04:18.120
it was a revolution, a
profound social revolution.

00:04:18.120 --> 00:04:20.250
You can imagine
also how difficult

00:04:20.250 --> 00:04:23.940
it was when, beyond that,
in the mid 16th century,

00:04:23.940 --> 00:04:27.660
Thomas Digges extended
the celestial sphere

00:04:27.660 --> 00:04:31.550
to innumerable stars going off
the page in every direction.

00:04:31.550 --> 00:04:33.890
Infinite numbers of stars.

00:04:33.890 --> 00:04:36.320
This was an
incomprehensible idea.

00:04:36.320 --> 00:04:38.120
It got people into trouble.

00:04:38.120 --> 00:04:40.520
This is the statue in the
Campo de Fiori in Rome

00:04:40.520 --> 00:04:42.440
of Giordano Bruno,
who was burned

00:04:42.440 --> 00:04:46.070
at the stake as a pertinacious
and impenitent heretic

00:04:46.070 --> 00:04:48.750
by the Catholic church,
for not only believing

00:04:48.750 --> 00:04:50.430
in an infinite
universe, but believing

00:04:50.430 --> 00:04:53.680
that those innumerable stars
had planets around them

00:04:53.680 --> 00:04:56.750
with lifeforms on them,
and perhaps people.

00:04:56.750 --> 00:04:59.170
And this was too much to bear.

00:04:59.170 --> 00:05:01.630
Cosmology is a
shifting landscape.

00:05:01.630 --> 00:05:03.560
The next venture
towards the infinite

00:05:03.560 --> 00:05:07.590
was Isaac Newton, who
postulated an infinite universe.

00:05:07.590 --> 00:05:11.330
Infinite in extent,
in time, and space.

00:05:11.330 --> 00:05:13.270
And this was followed
by Wright, who

00:05:13.270 --> 00:05:16.740
imagined infinite inhabited
worlds in this universe.

00:05:16.740 --> 00:05:18.710
It's still a difficult
concept, and it's

00:05:18.710 --> 00:05:20.520
difficult conceptually.

00:05:20.520 --> 00:05:23.210
If you were in a large
forest, every sightline

00:05:23.210 --> 00:05:25.540
through the forest
would end in a tree.

00:05:25.540 --> 00:05:27.980
In an infinite universe,
every sightline

00:05:27.980 --> 00:05:29.840
must end on a point
of light, whether it's

00:05:29.840 --> 00:05:31.780
a star or a galaxy.

00:05:31.780 --> 00:05:33.780
Since the light from
each star diminishes

00:05:33.780 --> 00:05:36.330
as the square of the distance,
but the number of stars

00:05:36.330 --> 00:05:39.800
rises by the same factor,
logically the night sky

00:05:39.800 --> 00:05:42.250
should be bright-- as
bright as the daytime sky--

00:05:42.250 --> 00:05:44.010
in an infinite universe.

00:05:44.010 --> 00:05:47.080
This was a paradox that
Newton never resolved.

00:05:47.080 --> 00:05:49.810
Not only infinite in light,
but infinite in gravity too,

00:05:49.810 --> 00:05:52.780
since that's an
inverse square law.

00:05:52.780 --> 00:05:55.440
So it took longer to learn
how the universe works,

00:05:55.440 --> 00:05:58.560
and to resolve Olber's paradox,
which, to cut to the chase,

00:05:58.560 --> 00:06:01.540
is resolved by the finite age
of the universe and the fact

00:06:01.540 --> 00:06:03.830
that it is expanding.

00:06:03.830 --> 00:06:05.360
Our sense of the
universe evolved

00:06:05.360 --> 00:06:07.830
through the time of
Herschel, making a catalog

00:06:07.830 --> 00:06:09.980
of fuzzy objects in the sky.

00:06:09.980 --> 00:06:12.360
Another dichotomy
arose as an argument

00:06:12.360 --> 00:06:15.580
over whether the Milky Way,
the system of stars we inhabit,

00:06:15.580 --> 00:06:17.750
was the whole universe
or whether there

00:06:17.750 --> 00:06:22.050
were other Island Universes,
systems of stars like our own.

00:06:22.050 --> 00:06:24.130
Herschel managed to
map out the Milky Way

00:06:24.130 --> 00:06:28.200
and knew it was vast, perhaps
100,000 light years across.

00:06:28.200 --> 00:06:29.800
But at the turn of
the 20th century,

00:06:29.800 --> 00:06:32.210
two very different
ideas were in play.

00:06:32.210 --> 00:06:34.380
In one of them,
the fuzzy nebulae--

00:06:34.380 --> 00:06:36.900
including the Andromeda
nebula, the easiest

00:06:36.900 --> 00:06:39.870
to study with big
telescopes-- were hypothesized

00:06:39.870 --> 00:06:42.640
to be distant systems of
stars like the Milky Way,

00:06:42.640 --> 00:06:46.520
perhaps hundreds of thousands
or millions of light years away.

00:06:46.520 --> 00:06:48.490
The countervailing
model, which was actually

00:06:48.490 --> 00:06:51.610
accepted through the
beginning of the 20th century,

00:06:51.610 --> 00:06:53.350
said that these fuzzy
patches of light

00:06:53.350 --> 00:06:55.070
were just regions
of star formation

00:06:55.070 --> 00:06:59.750
within our own large galaxy,
which was the universe.

00:06:59.750 --> 00:07:01.790
This was resolved
by Edwin Hubble, who

00:07:01.790 --> 00:07:05.370
made the breakthrough discovery
by measuring the distance,

00:07:05.370 --> 00:07:07.820
astronomically, to
the Andromeda nebula

00:07:07.820 --> 00:07:11.630
and a few dozen other
galaxies for the first time.

00:07:11.630 --> 00:07:15.110
The method he used involved
isolating variable stars

00:07:15.110 --> 00:07:18.150
within the body of the
galaxy and recognizing

00:07:18.150 --> 00:07:20.450
that they were identical
to similar variable stars

00:07:20.450 --> 00:07:22.220
in the Milky Way.

00:07:22.220 --> 00:07:24.830
Nature provides a
linear relationship

00:07:24.830 --> 00:07:27.270
between the absolute
brightness, or flux,

00:07:27.270 --> 00:07:30.410
from these variable stars
and relates it to the period.

00:07:30.410 --> 00:07:33.910
So by measuring the period of
variable stars in Andromeda,

00:07:33.910 --> 00:07:36.600
comparing them to local
examples at known distance,

00:07:36.600 --> 00:07:39.930
he was able to show that
Andromeda was several million

00:07:39.930 --> 00:07:40.950
light years away.

00:07:40.950 --> 00:07:43.820
It was an external galaxy.

00:07:43.820 --> 00:07:45.550
And by the end of
his career, he had

00:07:45.550 --> 00:07:47.440
extended the size of
the known universe

00:07:47.440 --> 00:07:49.230
by a factor of thousands.

00:07:49.230 --> 00:07:51.980
From a few thousand light
years to a few hundred

00:07:51.980 --> 00:07:55.450
million light years.

00:07:55.450 --> 00:07:56.860
That's the Hubble revolution.

00:07:56.860 --> 00:07:58.570
The second revolution
is to come,

00:07:58.570 --> 00:08:00.730
that of the expanding universe.

00:08:00.730 --> 00:08:04.130
But before going any further in
talking about a vast universe,

00:08:04.130 --> 00:08:07.490
let me remind you, as Guy
did last week, that cosmology

00:08:07.490 --> 00:08:09.060
involves assumptions.

00:08:09.060 --> 00:08:10.730
We don't know everything.

00:08:10.730 --> 00:08:13.190
The first assumption,
very profound,

00:08:13.190 --> 00:08:16.250
is that the universe is
in fact comprehensible.

00:08:16.250 --> 00:08:18.660
It's not necessarily the case.

00:08:18.660 --> 00:08:23.020
In fact, it's difficult to
keep the universe in your head.

00:08:23.020 --> 00:08:27.430
Another assumption is that the
universe obeys physical laws.

00:08:27.430 --> 00:08:29.600
It's a thing that has
been found magical

00:08:29.600 --> 00:08:31.190
to scientists and
mathematicians,

00:08:31.190 --> 00:08:33.530
that the universe
is so well described

00:08:33.530 --> 00:08:36.750
by simple and sometimes
complex mathematics,

00:08:36.750 --> 00:08:39.230
and by a very small set
of physical laws that

00:08:39.230 --> 00:08:41.000
seem to apply everywhere.

00:08:41.000 --> 00:08:44.520
It didn't have to be that way,
but it seems to be that way.

00:08:44.520 --> 00:08:47.190
These physical laws
remind us that our venture

00:08:47.190 --> 00:08:48.880
into the universe is incomplete.

00:08:48.880 --> 00:08:50.620
We don't know where
this will end.

00:08:50.620 --> 00:08:53.990
If we simplistically imagine
that the universe, nature,

00:08:53.990 --> 00:08:56.760
consists of things that happen
and things that don't, things

00:08:56.760 --> 00:08:59.670
that are and things that
aren't, the theory we have,

00:08:59.670 --> 00:09:01.950
being modest,
describes some subset

00:09:01.950 --> 00:09:03.910
of the things that
actually happen.

00:09:03.910 --> 00:09:05.200
It's not the theory we want.

00:09:05.200 --> 00:09:07.780
The theory we want is
the theory of everything.

00:09:07.780 --> 00:09:09.620
A theory that describes
everything that

00:09:09.620 --> 00:09:11.800
actually is in the universe.

00:09:11.800 --> 00:09:14.670
But the danger, of course, is
we don't know how to get there.

00:09:14.670 --> 00:09:17.650
And along the way, we
might, in our over-ambition,

00:09:17.650 --> 00:09:19.720
end up with a
theory of too much.

00:09:19.720 --> 00:09:23.090
And how would we
know the difference?

00:09:23.090 --> 00:09:25.180
Another way of looking
at this, and maybe

00:09:25.180 --> 00:09:27.120
a little more
profound, is the fact

00:09:27.120 --> 00:09:29.530
that we're bounded actually
not by our science,

00:09:29.530 --> 00:09:31.010
but or by our imaginations.

00:09:31.010 --> 00:09:35.177
And our imaginations are very
supple and very impressive.

00:09:35.177 --> 00:09:37.010
So there are the set
of things, for example,

00:09:37.010 --> 00:09:38.961
that are possible that
don't actually happen.

00:09:38.961 --> 00:09:41.210
That includes everything
that happens in the universe,

00:09:41.210 --> 00:09:43.290
plus some things that
break no law of nature,

00:09:43.290 --> 00:09:44.740
but don't actually happen.

00:09:44.740 --> 00:09:49.520
And if you wonder about the
things that you can imagine,

00:09:49.520 --> 00:09:51.910
the imaginable things hopefully
include all the things

00:09:51.910 --> 00:09:54.380
that do happen, but
maybe not all of them,

00:09:54.380 --> 00:09:56.970
almost certainly include a lot
of things that are possible,

00:09:56.970 --> 00:09:58.780
but not all of
them, and includes

00:09:58.780 --> 00:10:00.570
a lot of things that
just don't happen,

00:10:00.570 --> 00:10:02.030
but they're fun to think about.

00:10:02.030 --> 00:10:05.010
Once again, how do we
bound our imaginations

00:10:05.010 --> 00:10:07.490
in the universe that
has not yet presented us

00:10:07.490 --> 00:10:10.820
with all of its phenomena?

00:10:10.820 --> 00:10:14.230
We also assume that the universe
obeys very simple laws that

00:10:14.230 --> 00:10:16.950
says effects have causes.

00:10:16.950 --> 00:10:20.000
You have to think a bit to
realize how incomprehensible

00:10:20.000 --> 00:10:22.130
the universe would be
if causality did not

00:10:22.130 --> 00:10:23.860
operate at some level.

00:10:23.860 --> 00:10:27.260
Now note that this does
not imply determinism

00:10:27.260 --> 00:10:29.470
in the universe.

00:10:29.470 --> 00:10:32.700
Laplace famously caricatured
Newton's Law of Gravity

00:10:32.700 --> 00:10:35.534
by implying that if we knew
the positions and velocities

00:10:35.534 --> 00:10:36.950
of every particle
in the universe,

00:10:36.950 --> 00:10:39.330
we could predict the entire
future of the universe

00:10:39.330 --> 00:10:40.760
deterministically.

00:10:40.760 --> 00:10:43.330
Science is not
deterministic, but causality

00:10:43.330 --> 00:10:44.970
is a foundation stone.

00:10:44.970 --> 00:10:48.460
Without causality, events
could proceed causes.

00:10:48.460 --> 00:10:50.800
Things can move backwards
and forwards in time.

00:10:50.800 --> 00:10:54.020
And we know that that
is extremely tricky.

00:10:54.020 --> 00:10:56.920
We make another assumption
that is improperly

00:10:56.920 --> 00:11:00.640
tested by modern science, which
is that the laws of physics

00:11:00.640 --> 00:11:02.900
are the same everywhere.

00:11:02.900 --> 00:11:05.999
We do know that the
cosmological principle, which

00:11:05.999 --> 00:11:08.040
is the underlying assumption
that the universe is

00:11:08.040 --> 00:11:11.230
the same in every direction
and every location,

00:11:11.230 --> 00:11:13.600
is true in the sense
of every direction.

00:11:13.600 --> 00:11:16.590
Here looking across the sky,
we see roughly equal numbers

00:11:16.590 --> 00:11:19.010
of galaxies in each sideline.

00:11:19.010 --> 00:11:21.740
But testing it in location
is impossible because

00:11:21.740 --> 00:11:24.100
of the finite speed of light.

00:11:24.100 --> 00:11:25.600
If the speed of
light were infinite,

00:11:25.600 --> 00:11:29.060
we could see the entire
universe as it is now, laid out

00:11:29.060 --> 00:11:31.420
before us in its wonderfulness.

00:11:31.420 --> 00:11:33.420
But the speed of
light is finite,

00:11:33.420 --> 00:11:36.610
and that leads to a
very interesting issue.

00:11:36.610 --> 00:11:38.710
The issue of ancient light.

00:11:38.710 --> 00:11:41.580
Now cosmologists turn
the lemons into lemonade,

00:11:41.580 --> 00:11:43.960
and the fact that light
has a finite speed

00:11:43.960 --> 00:11:49.520
becomes an advantage because
it means that distant light is

00:11:49.520 --> 00:11:50.890
old light.

00:11:50.890 --> 00:11:52.780
The light that you
see reflecting off me

00:11:52.780 --> 00:11:55.200
from the stage lights
takes maybe a nanosecond

00:11:55.200 --> 00:11:56.300
to reach your eyes.

00:11:56.300 --> 00:11:58.190
You can't detect
that difference.

00:11:58.190 --> 00:12:00.350
You probably remember
the little time delay

00:12:00.350 --> 00:12:02.960
when people talk to the
astronauts at the moon.

00:12:02.960 --> 00:12:04.720
That's about a second.

00:12:04.720 --> 00:12:07.270
If you're talking about
the sun and some evil alien

00:12:07.270 --> 00:12:09.430
civilization squashed
it into a black hole

00:12:09.430 --> 00:12:11.380
and extinguished
its light, it would

00:12:11.380 --> 00:12:13.781
be eight minutes before
we were the wiser

00:12:13.781 --> 00:12:16.030
because that's how long it
would take that information

00:12:16.030 --> 00:12:17.310
to reach us.

00:12:17.310 --> 00:12:20.110
And it actually makes no
sense to ask of nature,

00:12:20.110 --> 00:12:21.960
what is the sun doing now?

00:12:21.960 --> 00:12:23.670
What is Sirius doing now?

00:12:23.670 --> 00:12:25.320
No, you have to be patient.

00:12:25.320 --> 00:12:26.880
You have to wait
those nine years

00:12:26.880 --> 00:12:29.570
for the light of that
bright star to reach you.

00:12:29.570 --> 00:12:32.060
And by the time you're in
the extra galactic universe,

00:12:32.060 --> 00:12:34.550
those light travel times
are becoming interesting.

00:12:34.550 --> 00:12:36.390
Far longer than a human life.

00:12:36.390 --> 00:12:40.220
Even the nearest galaxy is a
few million light years away,

00:12:40.220 --> 00:12:42.390
which means we see it
as it was in the past.

00:12:42.390 --> 00:12:45.590
And at the limit of our
telescopes, which I'll get to,

00:12:45.590 --> 00:12:46.970
they become time machines.

00:12:46.970 --> 00:12:51.220
And that's an extraordinary
thing to be given.

00:12:51.220 --> 00:12:53.820
A final assumption is
that our location is not

00:12:53.820 --> 00:12:55.590
special in the universe.

00:12:55.590 --> 00:12:58.540
And the more general
cultural way of saying that

00:12:58.540 --> 00:13:00.980
is that we are not
privileged in any way.

00:13:00.980 --> 00:13:03.250
I mean, occasionally it's
hard to get over the fact

00:13:03.250 --> 00:13:06.520
that we feel privileged, but
the Copernican revolution,

00:13:06.520 --> 00:13:09.770
if it's telling us anything,
is saying, get over yourselves.

00:13:09.770 --> 00:13:11.550
Just get over yourselves.

00:13:11.550 --> 00:13:14.460
You're not that special,
you're not that important.

00:13:14.460 --> 00:13:17.000
Starting with the Copernican
revolution itself,

00:13:17.000 --> 00:13:20.110
we have found that we are
not special in our location

00:13:20.110 --> 00:13:22.380
in our galaxy, and
our galaxy is not

00:13:22.380 --> 00:13:24.475
special in its location
in the universe.

00:13:24.475 --> 00:13:26.100
As I'll mention, we
found that were not

00:13:26.100 --> 00:13:28.580
even made of the stuff
the universe is made of.

00:13:28.580 --> 00:13:30.950
And the universe we
occupy may be one

00:13:30.950 --> 00:13:32.820
of a larger set of universes.

00:13:32.820 --> 00:13:34.620
And our biology
may not be unique.

00:13:34.620 --> 00:13:37.550
There's really nothing that
might be special about us

00:13:37.550 --> 00:13:39.880
in a cosmic sense.

00:13:39.880 --> 00:13:41.390
But this idea of
light travel time

00:13:41.390 --> 00:13:43.870
is critical to understanding
how the universe started,

00:13:43.870 --> 00:13:46.450
because it means to look at
how the universe started,

00:13:46.450 --> 00:13:49.770
all we have to do is look
out further and further.

00:13:49.770 --> 00:13:52.400
And so we have
the nearby now, we

00:13:52.400 --> 00:13:54.690
have the realm of the stars,
which is quite recent,

00:13:54.690 --> 00:13:56.540
maybe human lifetimes.

00:13:56.540 --> 00:14:00.010
We have long ago galaxies,
and for the universe itself,

00:14:00.010 --> 00:14:00.640
its ancient.

00:14:00.640 --> 00:14:03.644
Its looking back to
the dawn of time.

