00:17:16.000 --> 00:17:18.599
But let's return to what the
universe is made of before we

00:17:18.599 --> 00:17:22.484
go back in time
towards the Big Bang.

00:17:22.484 --> 00:17:24.400
Well talk about normal
matter first, the stuff

00:17:24.400 --> 00:17:26.220
that we're made of.

00:17:26.220 --> 00:17:30.580
99.9% of the universe
is hydrogen and helium.

00:17:30.580 --> 00:17:33.310
Rather uninteresting, and
the two simplest elements.

00:17:33.310 --> 00:17:34.860
Now, Phil [INAUDIBLE]
in a few weeks

00:17:34.860 --> 00:17:37.580
is going to talk
about the 0.1% that's

00:17:37.580 --> 00:17:41.200
left, but don't think of that as
a residue that's uninteresting,

00:17:41.200 --> 00:17:43.280
because without
that residue formed

00:17:43.280 --> 00:17:45.670
in the fiery heat of
stars, we wouldn't be here.

00:17:45.670 --> 00:17:47.960
That includes all
the nitrogen, carbon,

00:17:47.960 --> 00:17:51.030
and oxygen that life depends
on, the heavy elements.

00:17:51.030 --> 00:17:53.004
So that's a critical
part of the universe,

00:17:53.004 --> 00:17:54.420
but it's very
important that stars

00:17:54.420 --> 00:17:57.620
exist because if stars had
never formed in the congealing

00:17:57.620 --> 00:18:00.440
gas of the expanding
universe, the universe would

00:18:00.440 --> 00:18:02.189
have stayed hydrogen as helium.

00:18:02.189 --> 00:18:04.230
Now you know, I'm a
physicist, I'm not a chemist.

00:18:04.230 --> 00:18:06.230
But let me put my thinking
hat on and figure out

00:18:06.230 --> 00:18:10.710
what you can make with
hydrogen and helium.

00:18:10.710 --> 00:18:11.330
Nothing.

00:18:11.330 --> 00:18:13.550
You can't make anything
with hydrogen and helium.

00:18:13.550 --> 00:18:15.639
You can make a
hydrogen molecule, duh.

00:18:15.639 --> 00:18:17.430
And then you've got
helium, which is inert.

00:18:17.430 --> 00:18:18.540
That's really dull.

00:18:18.540 --> 00:18:21.540
Would be a dull universe
without stars, don't you think?

00:18:21.540 --> 00:18:23.810
That's the normal
matter, that's the atoms.

00:18:23.810 --> 00:18:25.030
And look how many there are.

00:18:25.030 --> 00:18:26.950
A one with 80 zeros after it.

00:18:26.950 --> 00:18:30.480
That's maybe the biggest
true pure number in science,

00:18:30.480 --> 00:18:32.450
because that's an
actual number of atoms.

00:18:32.450 --> 00:18:35.360
I know, I've counted-- no,
I haven't counted every one.

00:18:35.360 --> 00:18:37.490
Nobody has counted
everyone, it's an estimate.

00:18:37.490 --> 00:18:39.400
But it's pretty good.

00:18:39.400 --> 00:18:41.820
But it's actually eclipsed
by a factor of a billion

00:18:41.820 --> 00:18:43.730
by the number of
photons in the universe.

00:18:43.730 --> 00:18:47.560
There are a billion photons in
the universe for every atom.

00:18:47.560 --> 00:18:50.510
That's an interesting fact,
which will be fully explained,

00:18:50.510 --> 00:18:52.300
I think, by Mike
Turner next week,

00:18:52.300 --> 00:18:54.660
but I'll allude to where
it may have come from.

00:18:54.660 --> 00:18:56.820
Something we need to
explain about the universe,

00:18:56.820 --> 00:18:59.464
most of those photons
are unnoticed by us

00:18:59.464 --> 00:19:01.130
because they're dim
microwaves that I'll

00:19:01.130 --> 00:19:03.680
talk about in a few minutes.

00:19:03.680 --> 00:19:06.280
And those atoms, those 10
to the power of 80 atoms,

00:19:06.280 --> 00:19:09.980
are agglomerated into 100,000
billion billion stars--

00:19:09.980 --> 00:19:12.790
10 to the power of 23--
which typically are

00:19:12.790 --> 00:19:16.230
parsed 100 billion per galaxy.

00:19:16.230 --> 00:19:19.099
And there are a hundred billion
galaxies, round numbers,

00:19:19.099 --> 00:19:20.640
in the visible
universe, the universe

00:19:20.640 --> 00:19:22.170
we can see with our telescopes.

00:19:22.170 --> 00:19:26.170
So they're, in a nutshell, is
what the universe is made of.

00:19:26.170 --> 00:19:28.890
That's a lot of stars
and a lot of galaxies,

00:19:28.890 --> 00:19:32.000
and just to put a little forward
light onto Carolyn Porco,

00:19:32.000 --> 00:19:33.840
the last speaker in
this series, she's

00:19:33.840 --> 00:19:36.230
going to talk about the
proclivity of the universe

00:19:36.230 --> 00:19:38.720
for life, and she's going
to talk about the way

00:19:38.720 --> 00:19:40.600
we search for life
in the solar system.

00:19:40.600 --> 00:19:45.490
Our technology only lets us look
for biology in our backyard.

00:19:45.490 --> 00:19:46.900
So far.

00:19:46.900 --> 00:19:50.200
But what you should realize
is the cosmic number that

00:19:50.200 --> 00:19:52.600
based on the census
of Earth-like planets

00:19:52.600 --> 00:19:54.160
with the Kepler
Telescope and what

00:19:54.160 --> 00:19:56.960
we know from our backyard
in the Milky Way,

00:19:56.960 --> 00:20:00.750
the best guess is that there
are a billion billion Earths

00:20:00.750 --> 00:20:01.850
out there.

00:20:01.850 --> 00:20:02.770
More or less.

00:20:02.770 --> 00:20:04.180
Earth-like.

00:20:04.180 --> 00:20:06.580
That is an incredible number.

00:20:06.580 --> 00:20:08.804
And so you have to ask
yourself the question,

00:20:08.804 --> 00:20:10.720
since life started on
the earth almost as soon

00:20:10.720 --> 00:20:13.480
as you can imagine, when
the conditions were really

00:20:13.480 --> 00:20:16.110
inhospitable, do
you imagine that all

00:20:16.110 --> 00:20:19.180
of those billion billion
Earths out there are sterile

00:20:19.180 --> 00:20:21.370
and there's no biology
in any of them?

00:20:21.370 --> 00:20:23.060
Or put another way,
how many of them

00:20:23.060 --> 00:20:25.440
do you think have spawned
some interesting biological

00:20:25.440 --> 00:20:27.810
experiment, perhaps
even eclipsing

00:20:27.810 --> 00:20:30.550
the intelligence and
complexity of life on Earth?

00:20:30.550 --> 00:20:32.060
Wouldn't that be
nice to find out?

00:20:32.060 --> 00:20:36.400
But that's the cosmic context
for life in the universe.

00:20:36.400 --> 00:20:37.780
And these galaxies are real.

00:20:37.780 --> 00:20:40.220
We can observe them with
the Hubble deep telescope.

00:20:40.220 --> 00:20:43.840
The galaxies you see panning
across this tiny region of sky

00:20:43.840 --> 00:20:47.600
are all 10 or more million times
fainter than the eye can see.

00:20:47.600 --> 00:20:52.290
Each of them is within 10, 5
to 10 billion light years away,

00:20:52.290 --> 00:20:54.090
so you're looking
at an ancient light.

00:20:54.090 --> 00:20:56.760
And as you look at them,
each of these galaxies

00:20:56.760 --> 00:21:00.660
has roughly 100 million earths.

00:21:00.660 --> 00:21:02.790
You can imagine the
possibility that

00:21:02.790 --> 00:21:06.770
on some of these galaxies
across the eons of time, someone

00:21:06.770 --> 00:21:09.622
or something is
looking back at us.

00:21:20.720 --> 00:21:24.910
Each fuzzy smudge is a galaxy,
a distant system of stars,

00:21:24.910 --> 00:21:26.410
seen with the Hubble
Space Telescope

00:21:26.410 --> 00:21:28.540
in the deepest image ever made.

00:21:34.510 --> 00:21:36.910
That's the normal
matter, but in a surprise

00:21:36.910 --> 00:21:40.590
to astronomy that's now 30 or
40 years old so astronomers have

00:21:40.590 --> 00:21:42.770
gotten over their
surprise, the universe

00:21:42.770 --> 00:21:45.820
is made of six or
seven times more dark

00:21:45.820 --> 00:21:48.770
and mysterious material than
the light and visible stuff

00:21:48.770 --> 00:21:49.890
that we're familiar with.

00:21:49.890 --> 00:21:51.190
It's called dark matter.

00:21:51.190 --> 00:21:53.300
It's seen here, not
because we can see it,

00:21:53.300 --> 00:21:55.300
but this is a
computer simulation

00:21:55.300 --> 00:21:57.990
where we try and understand
the universe by spooning

00:21:57.990 --> 00:22:00.930
dark matter with the appropriate
properties into a computer,

00:22:00.930 --> 00:22:03.230
and seeing how it
structures over time.

00:22:03.230 --> 00:22:05.570
The dark matter
itself is invisible.

00:22:05.570 --> 00:22:07.050
So how do we know it's there?

00:22:07.050 --> 00:22:08.220
Good question.

00:22:08.220 --> 00:22:10.270
And was answered
painfully by astronomers

00:22:10.270 --> 00:22:12.110
over several decades.

00:22:12.110 --> 00:22:14.989
We weigh galaxies by
looking at star motions.

00:22:14.989 --> 00:22:17.280
Now if you looked at the
motions of stars near the sun,

00:22:17.280 --> 00:22:19.000
they're just milling
around randomly

00:22:19.000 --> 00:22:21.440
because the little cube
within 100 light years

00:22:21.440 --> 00:22:24.860
is partaking in a leisurely
quarter billion year orbit

00:22:24.860 --> 00:22:26.440
of the center of our galaxy.

00:22:26.440 --> 00:22:29.590
But if you map out the motion
of stars across the entire Milky

00:22:29.590 --> 00:22:32.150
Way, you see a
pattern of rotation

00:22:32.150 --> 00:22:34.190
which should have a
particular character

00:22:34.190 --> 00:22:36.440
if the mass of the
Milky Way is where

00:22:36.440 --> 00:22:38.440
you see the light, which
is where the stars are,

00:22:38.440 --> 00:22:40.380
which is what you expect.

00:22:40.380 --> 00:22:43.450
What astronomers saw, starting
actually 30 or 40 years ago,

00:22:43.450 --> 00:22:45.310
was something quite different.

00:22:45.310 --> 00:22:48.240
Again, if the galaxy's
mass was really just

00:22:48.240 --> 00:22:50.910
where its light was,
then by Kepler's law,

00:22:50.910 --> 00:22:53.820
you would expect the velocities
of those peripheral stars

00:22:53.820 --> 00:22:57.280
to start to decline because
you've seen past the mass.

00:22:57.280 --> 00:22:59.600
Just in the same way that
moving out from the sun,

00:22:59.600 --> 00:23:00.980
the velocities of
the planets all

00:23:00.980 --> 00:23:03.090
declined to the outer planets.

00:23:03.090 --> 00:23:05.110
What was seen was
not that at all.

00:23:05.110 --> 00:23:07.040
The velocities
continued high, even

00:23:07.040 --> 00:23:09.220
rising beyond the
distance of the sun

00:23:09.220 --> 00:23:11.540
to the outer edge
of the Milky Way.

00:23:11.540 --> 00:23:14.070
Not only in the Milky
Way, but in every spiral

00:23:14.070 --> 00:23:15.420
galaxy ever observed.

00:23:15.420 --> 00:23:18.700
This is a universal
phenomena as far as we know.

00:23:18.700 --> 00:23:20.520
And the only
sensible explanation

00:23:20.520 --> 00:23:24.119
for this in terms of gravity
is that the mass of a galaxy,

00:23:24.119 --> 00:23:25.660
if you just look at
its stars, you're

00:23:25.660 --> 00:23:28.340
underestimating by a
factor of six or seven.

00:23:28.340 --> 00:23:33.040
And that larger factor
additional is dark matter.

00:23:33.040 --> 00:23:35.440
The second way we've
measured it very convincingly

00:23:35.440 --> 00:23:37.480
is by gravity bending light.

00:23:37.480 --> 00:23:38.860
If you look at
the distant galaxy

00:23:38.860 --> 00:23:41.630
through a cluster of
galaxies between you

00:23:41.630 --> 00:23:44.770
and I-- between it and
us, mass bends light

00:23:44.770 --> 00:23:46.560
according to general relativity.

00:23:46.560 --> 00:23:48.500
And so the light of
those distant galaxies

00:23:48.500 --> 00:23:50.780
is stretched,
sheared, and amplified

00:23:50.780 --> 00:23:52.230
into little arcs of light.

00:23:52.230 --> 00:23:53.760
It's a very striking phenomenon.

00:23:53.760 --> 00:23:56.430
Can't be explained
any other way.

00:23:56.430 --> 00:23:57.930
This gravitational
lensing, as it's

00:23:57.930 --> 00:23:59.690
called, a prediction
of general relativity

00:23:59.690 --> 00:24:01.720
and a confirmation of
general relativity,

00:24:01.720 --> 00:24:05.560
is a way of weighing a cluster,
and also individual galaxies.

00:24:05.560 --> 00:24:08.310
And it confirms what
motions of stars do,

00:24:08.310 --> 00:24:13.127
that galaxies are dominated
by invisible matter.

00:24:13.127 --> 00:24:15.210
And the question becomes,
what is the dark matter?

00:24:15.210 --> 00:24:17.880
And all I can say at
this point, but we're

00:24:17.880 --> 00:24:20.300
optimistic within a
decade we may know,

00:24:20.300 --> 00:24:22.660
is play a game of elimination.

00:24:22.660 --> 00:24:25.840
First of all, why not question
your theory of gravity?

00:24:25.840 --> 00:24:28.330
And people have done
that, to be fair.

00:24:28.330 --> 00:24:30.380
The point is that the
gravity law, and that

00:24:30.380 --> 00:24:32.980
is Newton's law on large
scales and Einstein's law when

00:24:32.980 --> 00:24:36.070
gravity is strong, has
passed so many tests that

00:24:36.070 --> 00:24:38.220
were unwilling to throw
it away because then you

00:24:38.220 --> 00:24:40.220
throw everything away.

00:24:40.220 --> 00:24:43.140
And so the hypothesis has
become that there is a dark form

00:24:43.140 --> 00:24:44.980
of material in the universe.

00:24:44.980 --> 00:24:47.200
You can only make the
universe in a computer look

00:24:47.200 --> 00:24:50.190
like the universe we see if
you put dark matter into it.

00:24:50.190 --> 00:24:52.915
So far all we've done
is eliminate things.

00:24:52.915 --> 00:24:55.620
Well, black holes are dark,
maybe it could be black holes.

00:24:55.620 --> 00:24:57.610
No, because before
you have a black hole,

00:24:57.610 --> 00:25:00.090
