that's a pyrotechnic display

00:25:00.090 --> 00:25:02.060
that would be easy to find.

00:25:02.060 --> 00:25:03.950
Maybe they're just
dim normal stars?

00:25:03.950 --> 00:25:06.180
No, our stellar senses,
with things like the Hubble,

00:25:06.180 --> 00:25:07.340
is just too good.

00:25:07.340 --> 00:25:10.230
You can't hide stars in
sufficient quantities,

00:25:10.230 --> 00:25:12.250
because remember, you
need five or six times

00:25:12.250 --> 00:25:14.110
more than normal stars.

00:25:14.110 --> 00:25:17.700
What about things that are just
too low in mass to turn on,

00:25:17.700 --> 00:25:21.370
to ignite in fusion and so
they don't shine, so their dim?

00:25:21.370 --> 00:25:23.530
Dark things like brown
dwarfs, or even planets,

00:25:23.530 --> 00:25:24.940
free floating planets.

00:25:24.940 --> 00:25:25.820
Can't do it.

00:25:25.820 --> 00:25:27.800
Once again,
gravitational lensing

00:25:27.800 --> 00:25:30.510
would find the signature
of those insufficient

00:25:30.510 --> 00:25:34.430
if they were in that large
number, and that's ruled out.

00:25:34.430 --> 00:25:36.110
And then you can
go all the way down

00:25:36.110 --> 00:25:38.270
to mountain-sized
boulders in space,

00:25:38.270 --> 00:25:41.080
to things the size of your
fist, to microscopic dust

00:25:41.080 --> 00:25:43.390
grains just littering space.

00:25:43.390 --> 00:25:47.610
And indeed those things would
