00:28:05.240 --> 00:28:08.215
of the last century, but he
made a second discovery close

00:28:08.215 --> 00:28:09.715
on the heels of his
first discovery,

00:28:09.715 --> 00:28:12.460
and that the cosmic expansion.

00:28:12.460 --> 00:28:14.280
Hubble observed the
spectrum of galaxies

00:28:14.280 --> 00:28:17.440
shown in the visible
spectrum just turning light

00:28:17.440 --> 00:28:20.020
into a rainbow, and then
represented graphically

00:28:20.020 --> 00:28:23.327
where you track the wavelengths
of the sharp emission

00:28:23.327 --> 00:28:24.910
or absorption features
of the elements

00:28:24.910 --> 00:28:26.950
that galaxies and
stars are made of.

00:28:26.950 --> 00:28:29.650
And when you do that, you find
that the distant galaxies,

00:28:29.650 --> 00:28:32.340
the external galaxies
are always shifted.

00:28:32.340 --> 00:28:33.880
Very, very occasionally
to the blue,

00:28:33.880 --> 00:28:36.170
but almost entirely to the
red, to longer wavelengths.

00:28:36.170 --> 00:28:39.210
And sometimes, as in this
case, by a significant fraction

00:28:39.210 --> 00:28:40.200
of the speed of light.

00:28:40.200 --> 00:28:43.200
So they're moving
away very fast.

00:28:43.200 --> 00:28:46.010
Beyond that, he showed
a linear relationship

00:28:46.010 --> 00:28:48.990
between the recession velocity,
the speed of moving away--

00:28:48.990 --> 00:28:51.750
and its a large number,
1,000 kilometers per second

00:28:51.750 --> 00:28:53.210
there-- and the distance.

00:28:53.210 --> 00:28:56.370
MPC is megaparsec, that's
three million light years,

00:28:56.370 --> 00:28:58.470
so you're going out to
6 million light years.

00:28:58.470 --> 00:29:00.190
It's not a very
good correlation,

00:29:00.190 --> 00:29:03.210
but that was his first data
and it established the idea

00:29:03.210 --> 00:29:04.700
of an expanding universe.

00:29:04.700 --> 00:29:07.300
Since then, we've
expanded Hubble's relation

00:29:07.300 --> 00:29:08.725
by factors of 100.

00:29:08.725 --> 00:29:11.380
Hubble's original relation,
that previous graph,

00:29:11.380 --> 00:29:14.640
is the little blue dot that
would fit the origin here.

00:29:14.640 --> 00:29:18.460
With modern telescopes, we
now extend the regime out

00:29:18.460 --> 00:29:20.360
to 1 and 1/2
billion light years,

00:29:20.360 --> 00:29:22.930
and the perfect linear
relationship holds.

00:29:22.930 --> 00:29:25.730
The expansion, the cosmic,
linear, smooth expanding

00:29:25.730 --> 00:29:29.810
universe is valid on huge
scales of the universe.

00:29:29.810 --> 00:29:32.310
And it logically
begs the question,

00:29:32.310 --> 00:29:35.070
if everything is moving away
from everything else, what

00:29:35.070 --> 00:29:36.920
happens if you run
the clock backwards?

00:29:36.920 --> 00:29:39.700
Surely there was a time when
all the galaxies, now further

00:29:39.700 --> 00:29:42.830
apart than ever, were
on top of each other.

00:29:42.830 --> 00:29:45.940
And since the universe behaves
in some ways like a gas,

00:29:45.940 --> 00:29:49.730
the universe must have been
smaller, hotter, and denser.

00:29:49.730 --> 00:29:52.270
You also have your first
check on this idea,

00:29:52.270 --> 00:29:54.660
because we know how to
measure the age of the oldest

00:29:54.660 --> 00:29:56.731
stars in the galaxy.

00:29:56.731 --> 00:29:58.480
And on the principle
that you should never

00:29:58.480 --> 00:30:00.370
eat anything bigger
than your head,

00:30:00.370 --> 00:30:03.600
the universe should not be
younger than the oldest object

00:30:03.600 --> 00:30:04.770
that it contains.

00:30:04.770 --> 00:30:07.610
So that's a first check on
this expanding universe idea.

00:30:07.610 --> 00:30:10.130
For a while it wasn't clear
how well that check worked,

00:30:10.130 --> 00:30:11.380
but now it works.

00:30:11.380 --> 00:30:13.240
The age of the
universe projected

00:30:13.240 --> 00:30:15.650
by running the expansion
backwards in time

00:30:15.650 --> 00:30:18.570
is consistent with the
oldest stars we can find.

00:30:18.570 --> 00:30:21.160
And the age of the
universe is between 13,

00:30:21.160 --> 00:30:22.880
closer to 14 billion years.

00:30:22.880 --> 00:30:26.750
And actually now measured
with quite high precision.

00:30:26.750 --> 00:30:28.050
So what about this expansion?

00:30:28.050 --> 00:30:30.050
How can we understand
this expanding universe?

00:30:30.050 --> 00:30:32.740
Because it begs a
question, of course,

00:30:32.740 --> 00:30:34.389
is this violating Copernicus?

00:30:34.389 --> 00:30:35.930
If everything is
moving away from us,

00:30:35.930 --> 00:30:38.060
maybe we're special after all.

00:30:38.060 --> 00:30:39.630
I was really getting worried.

00:30:39.630 --> 00:30:41.290
You know, you're
all thinking you're

00:30:41.290 --> 00:30:43.200
going to have to buy
this crap about us

00:30:43.200 --> 00:30:44.430
being sort of insignificant.

00:30:44.430 --> 00:30:44.810
No, no.

00:30:44.810 --> 00:30:45.480
We're the center.

00:30:45.480 --> 00:30:46.000
It's OK.

00:30:46.000 --> 00:30:47.080
It's cool.

00:30:47.080 --> 00:30:48.200
Well no, we're not.

00:30:48.200 --> 00:30:51.680
We're not the center, because
here we are on the red galaxy

00:30:51.680 --> 00:30:53.970
and we look at galaxies--
the blue and the red one,

00:30:53.970 --> 00:30:54.770
for example.

00:30:54.770 --> 00:30:57.600
The blue and the green-- and we
see them moving away from us.

00:30:57.600 --> 00:30:59.490
And the more distant
one moves away faster,

00:30:59.490 --> 00:31:01.060
as Hubble's law said.

00:31:01.060 --> 00:31:03.460
But now translate
your point of view

00:31:03.460 --> 00:31:06.080
to the blue galaxy or the
red one, and look around

00:31:06.080 --> 00:31:07.480
and you see the same thing.

00:31:07.480 --> 00:31:09.850
Every galaxy sees
the same thing.

00:31:09.850 --> 00:31:13.540
It's a democracy of viewpoint,
and so no galaxy is the center.

00:31:13.540 --> 00:31:16.180
Every galaxy is the center,
no galaxy is the center.

00:31:16.180 --> 00:31:19.410
And presumably on this
blue galaxy, not ours,

00:31:19.410 --> 00:31:21.340
there is a planet
going around a star

00:31:21.340 --> 00:31:25.292
and someone not called Hubble,
who named the law after them.

00:31:25.292 --> 00:31:27.750
And they're going to argue with
Hubble when they eventually

00:31:27.750 --> 00:31:30.080
meet in whatever afterlife.

00:31:30.080 --> 00:31:32.534
No, that was my law,
I saw that first.

00:31:32.534 --> 00:31:34.200
Well did you account
for a lookback time

00:31:34.200 --> 00:31:35.449
when you say you saw it first?

00:31:38.030 --> 00:31:39.830
To describe the
expanding universe,

00:31:39.830 --> 00:31:42.880
you have to use general
relativity, which is definitely

00:31:42.880 --> 00:31:46.140
a whole different yarn
than Newton's theory, which

00:31:46.140 --> 00:31:47.750
is linear space and time.

00:31:47.750 --> 00:31:50.860
General relativity accommodate
the idea of curved spacetime,

00:31:50.860 --> 00:31:54.290
in fact, demands it, because
matter curves space--

00:31:54.290 --> 00:31:56.730
as we saw in the little
animation-- on small scales,

00:31:56.730 --> 00:31:59.777
but on the global scale as well.

00:31:59.777 --> 00:32:01.610
Here's what the Hubble
expansion looks like.

00:32:01.610 --> 00:32:03.693
So now we've got the idea
of curved space in play,

00:32:03.693 --> 00:32:05.820
we can use the little model.

00:32:05.820 --> 00:32:07.440
There is no sound
on this, is there?

