And when a single star dies,
it can rival the brightness

00:34:10.020 --> 00:34:12.760
of the galaxy, allowing
us-- because these

00:34:12.760 --> 00:34:15.580
are like standard light bulbs
when they explode-- to measure

00:34:15.580 --> 00:34:17.699
the distance to these galaxies.

00:34:17.699 --> 00:34:20.239
This allowed us to
take the linear Hubble

00:34:20.239 --> 00:34:22.590
law, the smooth
cosmic expansion,

00:34:22.590 --> 00:34:25.820
and project it to even
earlier lookback times.

00:34:25.820 --> 00:34:28.810
What we predicted, what
cosmology predicted,

00:34:28.810 --> 00:34:32.060
since the universe has mass
and mass will slow down

00:34:32.060 --> 00:34:35.929
the expansion, we predicted that
as you go further back in time,

00:34:35.929 --> 00:34:39.181
you should see either
constant or faster expansion.

00:34:39.181 --> 00:34:40.639
In other words,
the universe should

00:34:40.639 --> 00:34:44.690
have decelerated since five or
six or seven billion years ago.

00:34:44.690 --> 00:34:46.280
What was observed
with the red data

00:34:46.280 --> 00:34:49.030
points was that the universe
was expanding slower

00:34:49.030 --> 00:34:52.770
in the past, which implies that
it's accelerated since then.

00:34:52.770 --> 00:34:54.477
And that was a
complete surprise.

00:34:54.477 --> 00:34:56.810
Because we know of nothing
that should make the universe

00:34:56.810 --> 00:34:58.160
accelerate.

00:34:58.160 --> 00:35:01.430
And so it leads to the idea of
dark energy, which I will just

00:35:01.430 --> 00:35:03.720
introduce and leave
Mike Turner to do

00:35:03.720 --> 00:35:05.120
the heavy lifting next week.

00:35:05.120 --> 00:35:06.720
He's a theorist
and that's really

00:35:06.720 --> 00:35:08.205
one of his main subjects.

00:35:08.205 --> 00:35:10.580
And I will say very little
about it for the simple reason

00:35:10.580 --> 00:35:12.010
that we don't know what it is.

00:35:12.010 --> 00:35:14.860
It's indicated by the
observation I just showed.

00:35:14.860 --> 00:35:18.340
It's a repulsive force working
in opposition to gravity.

00:35:18.340 --> 00:35:20.670
Its absolute level
of strength is

00:35:20.670 --> 00:35:23.220
too weak to be understood
by conventional physics,

00:35:23.220 --> 00:35:26.470
the physics of the textbooks
you might have on your shelf.

00:35:26.470 --> 00:35:27.960
And that's about it.

00:35:27.960 --> 00:35:30.340
It doesn't seem to vary
over time and space,

00:35:30.340 --> 00:35:32.731
but that's not been
measured very well.

00:35:32.731 --> 00:35:34.980
And that's the third major
ingredient of the universe.

00:35:34.980 --> 00:35:37.710
So we end up with a universe
where definitely we're

00:35:37.710 --> 00:35:39.050
not the major part.

00:35:39.050 --> 00:35:41.040
In the pizza of
the universe, we're

00:35:41.040 --> 00:35:43.380
a kind of paltry little
slice that would barely

00:35:43.380 --> 00:35:46.260
keep a sparrow alive,
and the dark energy

00:35:46.260 --> 00:35:49.530
and the dark matter, the dark
forces that actually govern

00:35:49.530 --> 00:35:53.020
the cosmic expansion,
acceleration, and deceleration

00:35:53.020 --> 00:35:55.490
or the overwhelming entities.

00:35:55.490 --> 00:35:56.390
So let's look back.

00:35:56.390 --> 00:35:58.810
Let's see how close to
the Big Bang we can get.

00:35:58.810 --> 00:36:00.360
So here we are on
the right hand edge

00:36:00.360 --> 00:36:03.980
of the diagram in a big, empty,
cold universe looking back

00:36:03.980 --> 00:36:06.180
through time, through
the aging of galaxies

00:36:06.180 --> 00:36:09.220
towards the dawn of time
and a much smaller, denser,

00:36:09.220 --> 00:36:11.170
and hotter universe.

00:36:11.170 --> 00:36:13.180
We simulate this in computers.

00:36:13.180 --> 00:36:15.820
Now in the computer, the
expansion of the universe

00:36:15.820 --> 00:36:18.440
is done in the computer, and
when I show a simulation,

00:36:18.440 --> 00:36:20.380
that expansion
will be taken out.

00:36:20.380 --> 00:36:23.720
And so you can see that since
this expanding hot gas is

00:36:23.720 --> 00:36:25.550
thinning out,
gravity has to work

00:36:25.550 --> 00:36:29.410
against the expanding universe
to congeal stars and galaxies.

00:36:29.410 --> 00:36:32.510
In a sense, it's lucky
that it happened at all.

00:36:32.510 --> 00:36:34.750
Here's a simulation run
from half a billion years

00:36:34.750 --> 00:36:36.380
after the Big Bang
to the present day.

00:36:36.380 --> 00:36:39.250
It's a 300 million
lightyear cube.

00:36:39.250 --> 00:36:43.130
And you see it goes from an
initially smooth distribution

00:36:43.130 --> 00:36:46.240
to galaxies not
randomly distributed,

00:36:46.240 --> 00:36:48.800
but strung along sheets
and voids and filaments

00:36:48.800 --> 00:36:51.740
of large-- beautiful large
scale structure of galaxies,

00:36:51.740 --> 00:36:53.800
which is what we see
in the real universe.

00:36:53.800 --> 00:36:55.860
The next one is the
same, but rotating so you

00:36:55.860 --> 00:36:58.280
get a sense of the three
dimensional structures that

00:36:58.280 --> 00:36:59.310
form.

00:36:59.310 --> 00:37:01.010
And these structures
are sculpted

00:37:01.010 --> 00:37:04.960
by the single forest of gravity
acting over 12 billion years.

00:37:08.590 --> 00:37:11.430
So with our telescopes, here's
how far back we can look.

00:37:11.430 --> 00:37:14.020
Our frontier instrument is
still the Hubble Space Telescope

00:37:14.020 --> 00:37:16.069
until the James Webb
Space telescope,

00:37:16.069 --> 00:37:18.360
which the University of
Arizona has an interest in both

00:37:18.360 --> 00:37:19.490
of these telescopes.

00:37:19.490 --> 00:37:22.470
And you can see that we're
working our way back to a time

00:37:22.470 --> 00:37:25.190
that astronomers call the
dark ages, before there

00:37:25.190 --> 00:37:26.930
were any stars or galaxies.

00:37:26.930 --> 00:37:29.934
If the universe started hot and
smooth and with no structure,

00:37:29.934 --> 00:37:31.600
there must have been
a time before there

00:37:31.600 --> 00:37:35.550
was light of any kind, and
that's called the dark ages.

00:37:35.550 --> 00:37:38.790
Here's the deepest image
of the sky ever made again.

00:37:38.790 --> 00:37:42.590
In this area, [INAUDIBLE] the
sky would be the head of a pin,

00:37:42.590 --> 00:37:44.200
and there are about
4,000 galaxies

00:37:44.200 --> 00:37:46.590
if you cared to count them all.

00:37:46.590 --> 00:37:49.740
And just two weeks ago,
the largest redshift

00:37:49.740 --> 00:37:51.430
or most distant
galaxy was observed.

00:37:51.430 --> 00:37:55.100
This tiny little smudge
zooming in two steps, which

00:37:55.100 --> 00:37:58.630
is seen as it was
13 billion years ago

00:37:58.630 --> 00:38:01.140
in a universe that's not
much older than that.

00:38:01.140 --> 00:38:03.930
And that's pretty much the limit
of our ground-based optical

00:38:03.930 --> 00:38:06.090
telescopes, or space-based.

00:38:06.090 --> 00:38:08.280
So we've pretty much
seen to the edge of time,

00:38:08.280 --> 00:38:11.047
to the edge of the
visible universe.

00:38:11.047 --> 00:39:20.162
[MUSIC PLAYING]

00:39:20.162 --> 00:39:21.120
Well, that's the story.

00:39:21.120 --> 00:39:22.910
But there's more,
it gets weirder.

00:39:22.910 --> 00:39:25.360
Because if you look back
more than about five

00:39:25.360 --> 00:39:28.410
billion light years,
any two objects in space

00:39:28.410 --> 00:39:31.737
were moving apart faster
than the speed of light.

00:39:31.737 --> 00:39:33.570
Wait a minute, didn't
Einstein say something

00:39:33.570 --> 00:39:35.810
about the speed of light
being an absolute limit?

00:39:35.810 --> 00:39:38.090
That's his special
theory of relativity.

00:39:38.090 --> 00:39:40.707
You know, he didn't get
exhausted after that,

00:39:40.707 --> 00:39:42.040
though that's exhausting enough.

00:39:42.040 --> 00:39:43.530
He went on to the
general theory,

00:39:43.530 --> 00:39:45.001
which describes the universe.

00:39:45.001 --> 00:39:46.500
And the general
theory of relativity

00:39:46.500 --> 00:39:48.860
has no speed limit
applied to the universe

00:39:48.860 --> 00:39:50.510
and the cosmic expansion.

00:39:50.510 --> 00:39:53.250
If you trace the standard
Big Bang model back

00:39:53.250 --> 00:39:55.490
for most of the first
half of the universe,

00:39:55.490 --> 00:39:57.490
the universe was expanding
faster than light.

00:39:57.490 --> 00:40:00.200
Which means that the light
from those distant galaxies,

00:40:00.200 --> 00:40:02.060
as it was emitted,
those galaxies

00:40:02.060 --> 00:40:05.004
were moving away from
us faster than light.

00:40:05.004 --> 00:40:06.420
And it's only
because the universe

00:40:06.420 --> 00:40:09.440
decelerated subsequently
that light was

00:40:09.440 --> 00:40:11.890
able to eventually reach us.

00:40:11.890 --> 00:40:14.290
Now a complication on
that is dark energy,

00:40:14.290 --> 00:40:16.640
which is causing the
universe to accelerate.

00:40:16.640 --> 00:40:18.924
And that means,
even more weirdly,

00:40:18.924 --> 00:40:20.340
that some galaxies
that we've been

00:40:20.340 --> 00:40:22.360
able to grasp with
our telescopes

00:40:22.360 --> 00:40:25.770
will eventually have their light
taken away from the telescopes

00:40:25.770 --> 00:40:27.620
because once more
they'll be ripped

00:40:27.620 --> 00:40:30.720
faster than the speed of
light away from our view.

00:40:30.720 --> 00:40:33.600
It's pretty weird.

00:40:33.600 --> 00:40:36.270
And the implication of
faster than light expansion

00:40:36.270 --> 00:40:38.880
of the universe-- and this
is profound and important,

00:40:38.880 --> 00:40:41.540
and it's a standard part of
cosmology, not speculation,

00:40:41.540 --> 00:40:43.720
not the lunatic fringe
of the subject--

00:40:43.720 --> 00:40:46.255
is that the physical
universe, all that there is,

00:40:46.255 --> 00:40:49.330
is substantially,
maybe vastly larger

00:40:49.330 --> 00:40:50.820
than the observable
universe, what

00:40:50.820 --> 00:40:54.226
we can see to the limit of the
Hubble telescope or any other.

00:40:54.226 --> 00:40:57.410
In other words, those
100,000 billion billion

00:40:57.410 --> 00:41:01.290
stars in 100 billion galaxies
are not necessarily, and very

00:41:01.290 --> 00:41:03.510
likely, not all there is.

00:41:03.510 --> 00:41:06.250
That's just what we can see.

00:41:06.250 --> 00:41:07.509
So let's get back closer.

00:41:07.509 --> 00:41:09.050
Let's get real close
to the Big Bang,

00:41:09.050 --> 00:41:10.770
and in fact this is
the best evidence

00:41:10.770 --> 00:41:12.330
that the Big Bang happened.

00:41:12.330 --> 00:41:13.960
So when that person
sort of collars you

00:41:13.960 --> 00:41:16.760
in Walgreens or in a
supermarket queue and you

00:41:16.760 --> 00:41:19.260
happen to mention, they heard
you talking about the Big Bang

00:41:19.260 --> 00:41:20.990
and they say, what's
with that Big Bang thing?

00:41:20.990 --> 00:41:22.810
I don't believe that,
that sounds crazy.

00:41:22.810 --> 00:41:24.730
You say, no, no, listen.

00:41:24.730 --> 00:41:27.250
Let me tell you about
the microwave background.

00:41:27.250 --> 00:41:28.730
Because the
microwave background,

00:41:28.730 --> 00:41:32.150
now that will convince anyone
that the Big Bang happened.

00:41:32.150 --> 00:41:33.700
This is a picture
of the microwave

00:41:33.700 --> 00:41:36.540
sky from a satellite,
an exquisite image made

00:41:36.540 --> 00:41:38.790
just a year ago, but we've
been trying to gather

00:41:38.790 --> 00:41:40.180
this data for decades.

00:41:40.180 --> 00:41:42.230
And it's a baby picture
of the universe,

00:41:42.230 --> 00:41:46.120
looking far back before the
oldest life in those galaxies.

00:41:46.120 --> 00:41:48.600
So we can do much
better with this image,

00:41:48.600 --> 00:41:51.430
much closer to the Big Bang
than with visible telescopes.

00:41:51.430 --> 00:41:54.310
In fact, in the analogy,
this is like a picture of you

00:41:54.310 --> 00:41:56.120
when you were a few hours old.

00:41:56.120 --> 00:41:58.630
That's how early it is in
the history of the universe.

00:41:58.630 --> 00:42:03.210
It's a remarkable picture
from just under 400,000 years

00:42:03.210 --> 00:42:06.210
after the Big Bang, in a 14
billion year old universe.

00:42:06.210 --> 00:42:08.590
So you can think of the ratio.

00:42:08.590 --> 00:42:12.340
In that time, the universe has
expanded by a factor of 1,000.

00:42:12.340 --> 00:42:15.310
It's got 1,000 times bigger,
and 1,000 times cooler.

00:42:15.310 --> 00:42:18.070
The physics is
actually quite simple.

00:42:18.070 --> 00:42:20.840
And the way to understand why
we can get an image like this

00:42:20.840 --> 00:42:24.100
is that if you look at a cloud
in the sky, the edge of a cloud

00:42:24.100 --> 00:42:26.030
is not a physical
barrier, it's just

00:42:26.030 --> 00:42:28.810
the point in the cloud in which
the density of water vapor

00:42:28.810 --> 00:42:30.630
diminishes to the
point that light

00:42:30.630 --> 00:42:33.620
travels freely and reaches
your eyes, so you see an edge.

00:42:33.620 --> 00:42:37.080
Inside the cloud, there's
still water vapor, but more,

00:42:37.080 --> 00:42:38.720
and the light bounces around.

00:42:38.720 --> 00:42:40.340
So it was in the universe.

00:42:40.340 --> 00:42:42.590
Before 400,000 years
after the Big Bang,

00:42:42.590 --> 00:42:45.880
the universe was as dense
as the atmosphere of a star,

00:42:45.880 --> 00:42:48.270
and light could
not travel freely.

00:42:48.270 --> 00:42:51.220
After 400,000 years, the
radiation travels freely

00:42:51.220 --> 00:42:56.430
and we see an image of the
early universe from that era.

00:42:56.430 --> 00:43:00.010
Since that era, those
photons, that light,

00:43:00.010 --> 00:43:02.510
have been stretched
by a factor of 1,000.

00:43:02.510 --> 00:43:05.500
So not only does the expanding
universe carry galaxies away

00:43:05.500 --> 00:43:07.520
from each other,
the waves of light

00:43:07.520 --> 00:43:09.410
that travel through
expanding space

00:43:09.410 --> 00:43:13.330
are stretched by expanding
space by the same factor.

00:43:13.330 --> 00:43:15.850
And so visible
light, dim red light

00:43:15.850 --> 00:43:19.350
from the very early universe, is
stretched by a factor of 1,000

00:43:19.350 --> 00:43:20.800
into feeble microwaves.

00:43:20.800 --> 00:43:23.380
And that's what the
satellite is seeing.

00:43:23.380 --> 00:43:25.750
Those microwaves are everywhere.

00:43:25.750 --> 00:43:28.090
There's a million or so
in every breath you take.

00:43:28.090 --> 00:43:29.740
Right now they feel this room.

00:43:29.740 --> 00:43:30.750
They're ambient.

00:43:30.750 --> 00:43:33.580
Ambient radiation from the
Big Bang in the universe.

00:43:33.580 --> 00:43:37.280
Because they're microwaves,
they're not really noticeable.

00:43:37.280 --> 00:43:39.280
I've occasionally had
people get worried-- maybe

00:43:39.280 --> 00:43:42.120
in that same supermarket queue,
someone gets worried about it.

00:43:42.120 --> 00:43:42.200
What?

00:43:42.200 --> 00:43:43.660
Do you mean there are
microwaves in space?

00:43:43.660 --> 00:43:44.530
I might get sterile.

00:43:44.530 --> 00:43:47.360
You know, or something
bad might happen.

00:43:47.360 --> 00:43:49.750
And if you do the calculation,
I'll reassure everyone

00:43:49.750 --> 00:43:54.230
and, you know, that the
intrinsic radiation, the radio

00:43:54.230 --> 00:43:57.060
luminosity of the
microwaves around you

00:43:57.060 --> 00:43:59.600
is 10 to the minus 5
watts of radio power.

00:43:59.600 --> 00:44:02.210
So it's like a 10 millionth
of a light bulb worth of radio

00:44:02.210 --> 00:44:02.760
energy.

00:44:02.760 --> 00:44:04.465
It's not going to
sterilize anyone.

00:44:04.465 --> 00:44:05.965
And it's not really
very noticeable,

00:44:05.965 --> 00:44:08.630
which is why it
was hard to find.

00:44:08.630 --> 00:44:12.290
And the Big Bang, because it's
everywhere, is not a place.

00:44:12.290 --> 00:44:13.390
There is no place.

00:44:13.390 --> 00:44:15.290
It's every place and no place.

00:44:15.290 --> 00:44:17.480
It was a time, not a place.

00:44:17.480 --> 00:44:20.219
Very zen like, isn't it?

00:44:20.219 --> 00:44:22.010
And if you really want
to see the Big Bang,

00:44:22.010 --> 00:44:24.910
you don't need a fancy radio
telescope, just take your TV

00:44:24.910 --> 00:44:27.282
and tune it between
stations, and 1%

00:44:27.282 --> 00:44:29.240
of the speckles on the
phosphor of your screen,

00:44:29.240 --> 00:44:31.310
if you have an old
style phosphorus screen,

00:44:31.310 --> 00:44:35.430
are interactions of the phosphor
with the microwave background

00:44:35.430 --> 00:44:36.300
radiation.

00:44:36.300 --> 00:44:39.570
And although your friends
and kids and neighbors

00:44:39.570 --> 00:44:42.800
may think you're pretty weird
staring at a screen doing

00:44:42.800 --> 00:44:45.730
that, I assure you
that that station,

00:44:45.730 --> 00:44:47.817
the Big Bang station
is better than the crap

00:44:47.817 --> 00:44:48.900
on all the other channels.

00:44:48.900 --> 00:44:56.450
[AUDIENCE LAUGHING]

00:44:56.450 --> 00:44:58.800
So we can't really get
close to the Big Bang,

00:44:58.800 --> 00:45:02.500
but here's a cool thing that
a researcher in Virginia did.

00:45:02.500 --> 00:45:05.080
This is the interactions
of matter and radiation

00:45:05.080 --> 00:45:07.570
in the first 10 million
years of the universe

00:45:07.570 --> 00:45:11.200
shrunk to 10 seconds and
raised from a deep organ

00:45:11.200 --> 00:45:14.240
pitch of a large universe,
infinite large universe,

00:45:14.240 --> 00:45:15.140
to audible range.

00:45:15.140 --> 00:45:16.870
So it was boosted by 50 octaves.

00:45:16.870 --> 00:45:19.590
And this is what the Big
Bang actually sounded like.

00:45:19.590 --> 00:45:22.184
You didn't think I was going
to show you the Big Bang.

00:45:22.184 --> 00:45:24.619
[WHOOSHING SOUND]

00:45:24.619 --> 00:45:26.687
Actually I'm going to--
If we bring the sound up,

00:45:26.687 --> 00:45:28.270
I'll do that again
because that wasn't

00:45:28.270 --> 00:45:29.912
quite loud enough to hear.

00:45:29.912 --> 00:45:32.270
I'm going to rewind a little.

00:45:32.270 --> 00:45:35.560
[WHOOSHING SOUND]

00:45:35.560 --> 00:45:39.546
So that's a sonification of the
actual, physical interactions

00:45:39.546 --> 00:45:41.420
of the first 10 million
years of the universe

00:45:41.420 --> 00:45:45.710
shrunk to 10 seconds and
boosted by 50 octaves.

00:45:45.710 --> 00:45:48.130
And so now we can look
at the known universe

00:45:48.130 --> 00:45:51.610
all the way out from the roof of
the world to the dawn of time.

00:45:51.610 --> 00:47:13.446
[AMBIENT MUSIC PLAYING]

00:49:03.000 --> 00:49:06.200
So let's go back
as early as we can,

00:49:06.200 --> 00:49:09.840
and now I'm moving into the
part where we're not so sure.

00:49:09.840 --> 00:49:12.300
The things I've told you so
far are pretty conventional

00:49:12.300 --> 00:49:14.760
cosmology, they've been
established actually

00:49:14.760 --> 00:49:18.350
in some cases for a few decades
with better and better evidence

00:49:18.350 --> 00:49:19.230
and data.

00:49:19.230 --> 00:49:22.350
And for people who work on the
very early universe theorists,

00:49:22.350 --> 00:49:24.580
not like myself, I use
telescopes, you know,

00:49:24.580 --> 00:49:27.140
actually what happens after
the Big Bang is kind of dull.

00:49:27.140 --> 00:49:29.590
Like they don't really care.

00:49:29.590 --> 00:49:31.390
We're looking back
to the dawn of time

00:49:31.390 --> 00:49:34.640
now, even maybe before the
dark ages, if possible.

00:49:34.640 --> 00:49:36.870
An enormous success
of the Big Bang model

00:49:36.870 --> 00:49:39.890
that's not as well publicized
as the microwave background

00:49:39.890 --> 00:49:41.570
is the fact that we
have physics that's

00:49:41.570 --> 00:49:45.010
tested in the first three
minutes after the Big Bang.

00:49:45.010 --> 00:49:47.420
So a 13.7 billion
year old universe,

00:49:47.420 --> 00:49:50.260
we have solidly
tested astrophysics.

00:49:50.260 --> 00:49:52.672
Because the amount of
helium in the universe--

00:49:52.672 --> 00:49:54.880
remember the universe is
mostly hydrogen and helium--

00:49:54.880 --> 00:49:58.560
is too much to have been
produced by normal processes

00:49:58.560 --> 00:50:00.990
in 100,000 billion
billion stars.

00:50:00.990 --> 00:50:02.830
We understand stars very well.

00:50:02.830 --> 00:50:05.810
There is not enough helium
made in all those stars

00:50:05.810 --> 00:50:09.180
to make one quarter of the
mass of the universe's helium.

00:50:09.180 --> 00:50:11.370
However, the entire
universe three minutes

00:50:11.370 --> 00:50:13.389
after the Big Bang
was the temperature

00:50:13.389 --> 00:50:14.430
of the center of the sun.

00:50:14.430 --> 00:50:17.740
And like the sun, it made
helium and other light elements.

00:50:17.740 --> 00:50:19.950
It didn't do it for long
because it was expanding.

00:50:19.950 --> 00:50:21.620
The sun is stable.

00:50:21.620 --> 00:50:25.170
And in fact not only helium,
but three other light elements

00:50:25.170 --> 00:50:28.020
have their abundances
measured in space,

00:50:28.020 --> 00:50:31.502
and their abundances of four
different light element species

00:50:31.502 --> 00:50:35.300
match a single parameter, a
single quantity in the Big Bang

00:50:35.300 --> 00:50:38.040
model, which is the
density of order of matter.

00:50:38.040 --> 00:50:42.320
That 4% slice of the cosmic pie.

00:50:42.320 --> 00:50:44.720
This is a stunning success
of the Big Bang model

00:50:44.720 --> 00:50:46.680
because otherwise you
have to explain where

00:50:46.680 --> 00:50:49.440
these light elements came from,
and there's no other mechanism

00:50:49.440 --> 00:50:50.510
to explain them.

00:50:50.510 --> 00:50:53.470
But the Big Bang
brilliantly explains

00:50:53.470 --> 00:50:56.230
something that happened
in the first few minutes.

00:50:56.230 --> 00:50:58.770
That's our largest
lookback time where

00:50:58.770 --> 00:51:02.220
we have a benchmark in
very understood physics.

00:51:02.220 --> 00:51:04.660
However we can trace the
expansion all the way back

00:51:04.660 --> 00:51:06.460
on a logarithmic
plot, you can see

00:51:06.460 --> 00:51:09.110
going to crazy small
fractions of a second.

00:51:09.110 --> 00:51:10.860
And, you know,
there are theorists

00:51:10.860 --> 00:51:13.330
who are quite happy to
explore the first fractions

00:51:13.330 --> 00:51:15.460
of a second, and
next week you're

00:51:15.460 --> 00:51:17.660
going to enter the realm here.

00:51:17.660 --> 00:51:19.370
You're going to
enter this realm.

00:51:19.370 --> 00:51:23.170
If you ask, where's our
tether, our last tether

00:51:23.170 --> 00:51:26.170
on the world of the real,
on the world of the lab?

00:51:26.170 --> 00:51:27.110
It's here.

00:51:27.110 --> 00:51:29.760
That's the limit of the
Large Hadron Collider, which

00:51:29.760 --> 00:51:32.610
for an instant, under very
special circumstances,

00:51:32.610 --> 00:51:35.140
can create this incredible
temperature of tens

00:51:35.140 --> 00:51:37.610
of trillions of degrees,
10 trillion degrees, which

00:51:37.610 --> 00:51:41.000
corresponds to the Big
Bang about a nanosecond

00:51:41.000 --> 00:51:42.490
after it happened.

00:51:42.490 --> 00:51:45.450
So lab physics can
corroborate the Big Bang

00:51:45.450 --> 00:51:47.170
all the way back to here.

00:51:47.170 --> 00:51:50.790
Beyond here, or before
here, demons lurk.

