I'm glad I wasn't
around, actually.

00:55:19.090 --> 00:55:21.310
Another thing that Mike
will talk about next week

00:55:21.310 --> 00:55:22.830
is something called inflation.

00:55:22.830 --> 00:55:25.670
It's a hypothetical
era-- very early,

00:55:25.670 --> 00:55:28.860
look at the crazy small number,
10 to the minus 35 seconds--

00:55:28.860 --> 00:55:31.690
when the universe inflated
from many times smaller

00:55:31.690 --> 00:55:34.494
than a proton to about
the size of a tennis ball.

00:55:34.494 --> 00:55:36.410
That's a nice, familiar
object, a tennis ball.

00:55:36.410 --> 00:55:38.750
We can imagine the
universe as a tennis ball.

00:55:38.750 --> 00:55:41.170
And we use inflation--
it's motivated

00:55:41.170 --> 00:55:44.270
by this merger of
forces as a mechanism--

00:55:44.270 --> 00:55:46.800
but we use inflation to
explain why the universe is

00:55:46.800 --> 00:55:49.350
so smooth and flat,
which otherwise is not

00:55:49.350 --> 00:55:50.980
a feature of the
standard Big Bang.

00:55:50.980 --> 00:55:54.390
It's not explained naturally
in the Big Bang model.

00:55:54.390 --> 00:55:56.860
What we're really reaching
for is a theory of everything

00:55:56.860 --> 00:55:58.530
that incorporates gravity.

00:55:58.530 --> 00:56:00.599
Now you know-- this,
you may-- everyone's

00:56:00.599 --> 00:56:02.390
entitled to their own
theory of everything.

00:56:02.390 --> 00:56:02.890
It's fine.

00:56:02.890 --> 00:56:04.880
There can be 1,000
theories of everything.

00:56:04.880 --> 00:56:07.450
Let 1,000 flowers bloom.

00:56:07.450 --> 00:56:09.750
Now you probably know
that Einstein fruitlessly

00:56:09.750 --> 00:56:12.570
spent the last 15 years
of his career searching

00:56:12.570 --> 00:56:15.450
for a unified theory that
incorporated gravity.

00:56:15.450 --> 00:56:17.470
It's a very hard thing to do.

00:56:17.470 --> 00:56:19.740
The current frontier
theory-- which

00:56:19.740 --> 00:56:22.840
I will just skate over very
briefly, it's beyond my domain

00:56:22.840 --> 00:56:24.930
here, and you'll hear
more about it next week--

00:56:24.930 --> 00:56:27.700
is string theory, which
postulates another,

00:56:27.700 --> 00:56:31.210
deeper level of structure
beyond the electrons,

00:56:31.210 --> 00:56:33.140
protons, neutrons,
and quarks that we're

00:56:33.140 --> 00:56:36.180
familiar with in our
standard model of physics.

00:56:36.180 --> 00:56:38.150
So these are
extraordinary ideas that

00:56:38.150 --> 00:56:41.530
postulate tiny, one dimensional
entities vastly smaller

00:56:41.530 --> 00:56:44.810
than a proton, which
compose everything.

00:56:44.810 --> 00:56:46.330
Which compose
everything there is.

00:56:46.330 --> 00:56:49.340
And they're motivated
by extremely beautiful

00:56:49.340 --> 00:56:51.860
but extremely
difficult mathematics.

00:56:51.860 --> 00:56:53.970
These theories of
nature only work

00:56:53.970 --> 00:56:58.100
when there are about 10 or
11 space time dimensions.

00:56:58.100 --> 00:57:00.310
And the mathematics, of
course, is very difficult.

00:57:00.310 --> 00:57:01.600
This has not been observed.

00:57:01.600 --> 00:57:04.320
It's extremely
hypothetical theorizing

00:57:04.320 --> 00:57:06.950
that's reaching for
another level of structure.

00:57:06.950 --> 00:57:08.620
If it's relevant
at all, though, it

00:57:08.620 --> 00:57:10.560
must be relevant to
the early universe,

00:57:10.560 --> 00:57:14.020
as well as to what
matter is made of.

00:57:14.020 --> 00:57:16.820
And so we actually are
faced with the probability,

00:57:16.820 --> 00:57:20.730
to use the word that's relevant,
that the universe is a quantum

00:57:20.730 --> 00:57:22.850
entity.

00:57:22.850 --> 00:57:26.460
It upset Einstein
very much, you know.

00:57:26.460 --> 00:57:29.660
All that damned quantum jumping.

00:57:29.660 --> 00:57:32.550
It spoiled his
idea of God, which

00:57:32.550 --> 00:57:34.980
I tell you frankly is the only
I get of Einstein's I never

00:57:34.980 --> 00:57:35.690
understood.

00:57:35.690 --> 00:57:38.480
He believed in the
same God as Newton.

00:57:38.480 --> 00:57:40.510
Causality, nothing
without a reason.

00:57:40.510 --> 00:57:44.700
But now one thing led to another
until causality was dead.

00:57:44.700 --> 00:57:50.330
Quantum mechanics made
everything finally random.

00:57:50.330 --> 00:57:52.210
A thing could be
this way or that way.

00:57:52.210 --> 00:57:54.390
The mathematics
deny certainty, they

00:57:54.390 --> 00:57:56.950
reveal only
probability and chance.

00:57:56.950 --> 00:58:01.355
And Einstein couldn't believe
in a God who threw dice.

00:58:05.218 --> 00:58:06.710
He should've come to me.

00:58:06.710 --> 00:58:09.220
I would have told him,
listen, Albert he threw you.

00:58:09.220 --> 00:58:09.720
Look around.

00:58:09.720 --> 00:58:10.428
He never stopped.

00:58:13.170 --> 00:58:16.080
Well you've been a good audience
