00:58:16.080 --> 00:58:19.190
so one last little turn
in the rollercoaster

00:58:19.190 --> 00:58:21.690
that hopefully doesn't
eject you at a high speed

00:58:21.690 --> 00:58:23.170
and a high height.

00:58:23.170 --> 00:58:24.730
I'll talk about the
multiverse, which

00:58:24.730 --> 00:58:28.010
is a frontier idea based
on the idea of the universe

00:58:28.010 --> 00:58:30.960
as a quantum originating event.

00:58:30.960 --> 00:58:34.750
Which logically leads to the
possibility of other quantum

00:58:34.750 --> 00:58:36.210
events.

00:58:36.210 --> 00:58:38.480
In the inflationary idea--
which you will definitely

00:58:38.480 --> 00:58:40.271
hear more about if you
go next week, that's

00:58:40.271 --> 00:58:43.420
Mike Turner's specialty, one
of his specialties-- inflation

00:58:43.420 --> 00:58:45.960
this early epoch of
very rapid expansion

00:58:45.960 --> 00:58:48.680
from micro microscopic
scales to the beginning

00:58:48.680 --> 00:58:52.620
of a macroscopic scale actually
stretched quantum fluctuations

00:58:52.620 --> 00:58:56.250
into ripples that became the
seed for galaxies to form.

00:58:56.250 --> 00:58:58.600
So in that microwave
map of the sky

00:58:58.600 --> 00:59:01.890
with the red, yellow, and blue
colors, those little speckles

00:59:01.890 --> 00:59:03.970
that are about a degree
across in the sky,

00:59:03.970 --> 00:59:06.140
if inflation is
correct, the speckles

00:59:06.140 --> 00:59:09.930
are quantum fluctuations
boosted to the size of galaxies

00:59:09.930 --> 00:59:13.010
that would subsequently evolve
into systems of hundreds

00:59:13.010 --> 00:59:14.330
of billions of stars.

00:59:14.330 --> 00:59:17.700
Quite a wild idea, isn't it?

00:59:17.700 --> 00:59:21.070
And it's the basis for the
idea of parallel universes,

00:59:21.070 --> 00:59:23.990
because if you have a set
of quantum fluctuations

00:59:23.990 --> 00:59:27.100
originating at the origin
of time and space, then

00:59:27.100 --> 00:59:30.790
you have a mechanism where our
inflating bubble of space time

00:59:30.790 --> 00:59:31.960
is not the only one.

00:59:31.960 --> 00:59:33.090
There can be many.

00:59:33.090 --> 00:59:36.280
And because of the random
nature of quantum fluctuations,

00:59:36.280 --> 00:59:38.430
those parallel
universes, if you like,

00:59:38.430 --> 00:59:40.430
will be randomly different
in their properties.

00:59:40.430 --> 00:59:43.320
They won't all be like this one.

00:59:43.320 --> 00:59:46.710
How do we understand these
randomly different universes?

00:59:46.710 --> 00:59:48.312
Well, we reach
for string theory.

00:59:48.312 --> 00:59:50.520
And string theory doesn't
help very much because it's

00:59:50.520 --> 00:59:53.070
too difficult to calculate in,
but the best string theorists

00:59:53.070 --> 00:59:54.920
will tell you is
that there are 10

00:59:54.920 --> 00:59:57.960
to the power 500
different possible vacuum

00:59:57.960 --> 00:59:59.480
states in string theory.

00:59:59.480 --> 01:00:01.980
And so that is the basis
for the multiverse.

01:00:01.980 --> 01:00:04.152
That's plenty of
universes, you know?

01:00:04.152 --> 01:00:05.610
I think E.E. Cummings
said, there's

01:00:05.610 --> 01:00:07.680
a hell of a universe
next door, let's go.

01:00:07.680 --> 01:00:10.500
Well, there's a lot of
universes next door,

01:00:10.500 --> 01:00:12.430
except we can't
really reach them.

01:00:12.430 --> 01:00:14.800
So quantum fluctuations
and string theory

01:00:14.800 --> 01:00:17.440
provide this
context for the idea

01:00:17.440 --> 01:00:21.090
that our universe was
not a unique event.

01:00:21.090 --> 01:00:22.550
And how can we test that?

01:00:22.550 --> 01:00:24.130
Of course that's
the current question

01:00:24.130 --> 01:00:25.600
on the plate of cosmologists.

01:00:25.600 --> 01:00:27.670
Is this a testable idea?

01:00:27.670 --> 01:00:29.590
String theory is
difficult enough to test,

01:00:29.590 --> 01:00:31.630
let alone the idea
of a multiverse.

01:00:31.630 --> 01:00:33.894
So I won't pretend that
it has been tested,

01:00:33.894 --> 01:00:35.560
and I won't even
pretend that it can be.

01:00:35.560 --> 01:00:38.310
It's a frontier idea
that we hope maybe

01:00:38.310 --> 01:00:40.990
in a decade or so
to be able to test.

01:00:40.990 --> 01:00:43.670
And so in this
inflationary model,

01:00:43.670 --> 01:00:47.030
different space times spawn
with different laws of physics,

01:00:47.030 --> 01:00:49.560
and the idea is that our
universe is quite special

01:00:49.560 --> 01:00:52.580
because it was long lived
and it formed stars,

01:00:52.580 --> 01:00:54.840
and the stars made
carbon, and the carbon

01:00:54.840 --> 01:00:57.030
sat around long enough at
inequitable temperature

01:00:57.030 --> 01:00:59.120
to make biology, and then us.

01:00:59.120 --> 01:01:02.690
Many of these universes spawning
from different conditions

01:01:02.690 --> 01:01:04.520
would be grossly inhospitable.

01:01:04.520 --> 01:01:07.740
Universes that had only
anti-matter, or equal

01:01:07.740 --> 01:01:08.900
anti-matter and matter.

01:01:08.900 --> 01:01:11.750
Universes that lasted a
microsecond and are gone again.

01:01:11.750 --> 01:01:14.000
Universes where
there's no causality.

01:01:14.000 --> 01:01:16.750
Every imaginable
universe could be there.

01:01:16.750 --> 01:01:20.300
And so our universe is perhaps
one of the few hospitable ones

01:01:20.300 --> 01:01:23.250
to life in the
multiverse concept.

